	<marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="520">
		<marc:subfield code="a">Preface</marc:subfield>
		<marc:subfield code="b">The preface.</marc:subfield>
		<marc:subfield code="c">Front</marc:subfield>
		<marc:subfield code="x">First lines read: &quot;The eastern way of writing hath been justly admired in all ages.  The bold metaphors and noble simplicity almost peculiar to the orientals add a lustre to their compositions, not to be rivalled by the greatest orators of Greece and Rome.&quot;</marc:subfield>
		<marc:subfield code="x">Comments on translations from Arabic: &quot; [...] even the English reader may form some idea of their sublime writings, by the translation of the scriptures, which yet falls infinitely short of the divine original. The blooming flowers of the east lose a great deal of their fragrancy and liveliness of color, become more languid and sickly, by being transplanted to the colder climates of the North [...] I have, in the following pages, endeavoured to shadow out some of the beauties of the original Arabic; and if I have failed in the copy, I hope the candid reader will pardon me, since the picture is almost inimitable, at least a very difficult task for an unexperienced hand.&quot;</marc:subfield>
	</marc:datafield>
	<marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="520">
		<marc:subfield code="a">Footnotes</marc:subfield>
		<marc:subfield code="c">Front</marc:subfield>
		<marc:subfield code="c">Middle</marc:subfield>
		<marc:subfield code="x">Footnote in the preface, p. ii: &quot;Vide Longinus de sublimate.&quot; Reference to the world external to the novel.</marc:subfield>
		<marc:subfield code="x">A footnote that appears on p. 3 of the text clarifies a reference to the world external to the novel.</marc:subfield>
		<marc:subfield code="x">A footnote on p. 11 references a literary work external to the novel.</marc:subfield>
	</marc:datafield>
	<marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="520">
		<marc:subfield code="a">Appendix</marc:subfield>
		<marc:subfield code="b">Appendix</marc:subfield>
		<marc:subfield code="c">Back</marc:subfield>
		<marc:subfield code="x">Includes a letter</marc:subfield>
		<marc:subfield code="x">First lines read: &quot;I hope it will not be thought impertinent here to subjoin a translation of Cassem\'s letter to Helim, his late preceptor. It was written a few days before his death, and contains his most private sentiments, which he freely unbosoms to his friend: for it seems he always had a tender regard for Helim, and communicated his thoughts to him with less reserve than to any of his preceptors.&quot;</marc:subfield>
		<marc:subfield code="x">Letter: &quot;[...] Thou gavest me first to know the supreme goodness that made me; and didst teach my lisping infant tongue to celebrate the praises of the all-gracious Allah. Thy wisdom conducted me through the regions of immensity; shewed me the various systems that fill the unmeasured space, and taught me how the jarring elements were harmonized by the creator\'s all-powerful word.&quot;</marc:subfield>
	</marc:datafield>
	<marc:datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="590">
